U.S. and Japanese stock futures slid and the yen rose after President Donald Trump ordered his administration to consider tariffs on an additional $100 billion worth of Chinese imports, dashing investor optimism that trade tensions could ease with negotiations on the horizon. The release of Trump’s statement upended what had been poised to be a positive session for Asian equities, after the U.S. S&P 500 Index had climbed for a third straight session thanks in part to comments from White House officials indicating talks were in the offing between the world’s top two economies. Futures on the S&P 500 and Japan’s Nikkei 225 were down more than 1 percent Friday morning in Asia. Chinese markets are shut for a holiday. Crude oil prices dropped and gold rallied. Ten-year Treasury yields on Thursday had popped above 2.83 percent ahead of the March U.S. employment report, which will feed into the outlook for Federal Reserve interest-rate hikes. Analysts remain divided on whether two or three more increases in the benchmark policy target are coming by year-end. See our live blog on the latest round in trade tensions. Here are some key events for the remainder of this week: And these are the main moves in markets: